1
00:00:00,880 --> 00:00:19,060
Fall has arrived, heating season's starting, and we decided to build an interesting setup — at the same time testing whether you can heat a radiator like this without a circulation pump.

2
00:00:20,220 --> 00:00:23,480
Pump-less means without an extra pump.

3
00:00:24,960 --> 00:00:30,780
Last night we got all the parts ready for assembling a small boiler.

4
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:36,780
We'll heat it with electricity, using this kind of heating element.

5
00:00:38,700 --> 00:00:41,320
Now we'll weld it all together.

6
00:00:42,860 --> 00:00:46,380
These, say, will be the outlets to the radiator.

7
00:00:47,780 --> 00:01:00,060
The concern is that the cross-section for water flow is a bit narrow for normal water circulation through the radiator.

8
00:01:00,740 --> 00:01:05,680
So we'll put it together now and check whether it actually works.

9
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:11,540
We picked up a small expansion tank at the store.

10
00:01:12,720 --> 00:01:14,700
Not cheap — 600 rubles.

11
00:01:16,580 --> 00:01:18,220
No way around it.

12
00:01:18,220 --> 00:01:27,880
This is a valve that'll trip if water pressure in the system goes past a dangerous mark.

13
00:01:28,920 --> 00:01:38,820
Plus metal union fittings, so it's easy to hook this boiler up to the radiator.

14
00:01:40,420 --> 00:01:46,600
We'll weld it, fire it up, test it, and see whether this approach works.

15
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:51,260
Although the plumbers told us it wouldn't.

16
00:01:52,440 --> 00:01:53,220
Let's try it.

17
00:01:56,160 --> 00:02:05,560
We started welding the bottom hole where the heating element will go.

18
00:02:06,040 --> 00:02:11,120
To avoid damaging the thread, we filled it with pebbles.

19
00:02:20,070 --> 00:02:25,410
Our helper is ready to help — or break something.

20
00:02:30,100 --> 00:02:34,000
We welded the bottom cap.

21
00:02:35,640 --> 00:02:37,200
Here's what we ended up with.

22
00:02:37,740 --> 00:02:40,400
The heating element will screw into this threaded hole.

23
00:02:41,280 --> 00:02:45,120
Now moving on to welding the top cap.

24
00:02:46,320 --> 00:02:57,420
The top cap is for filling water, and we'll add an outlet to vent excess air from the boiler.

25
00:02:58,220 --> 00:03:05,060
We gave it a dome shape so air doesn't pocket in the corners.

26
00:03:05,480 --> 00:03:13,540
Now we'll weld the threaded fitting here and move on to assembling the boiler.

27
00:03:16,660 --> 00:03:32,500
This way we lined up the inlet axis with the radiator and tacked our radiator-side fittings in place.

28
00:03:34,540 --> 00:03:44,800
Now we'll take off the metal union fittings and weld all the way around, just like we did with this hole.

29
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:51,320
After that, just plug it up and check whether it holds water.

30
00:03:51,720 --> 00:03:53,580
And then on to testing.

31
00:03:54,300 --> 00:04:02,220
We welded the hole, and it didn't quite match the layout marks.

32
00:04:03,660 --> 00:04:09,800
You can see the metal sticks out a bit here.

33
00:04:10,120 --> 00:04:15,180
But that's no problem — every millimeter of the passage matters now.

34
00:04:15,860 --> 00:04:21,200
Our trusty file will fix that — it'll quickly smooth out any irregularities.

35
00:04:21,460 --> 00:04:22,080
Off we go.

36
00:04:24,220 --> 00:04:28,580
Our build is taking shape.

37
00:04:29,480 --> 00:04:37,960
Welded the hole, cleaned up the outlets with a file, and now you can see what we had in mind.

38
00:04:39,120 --> 00:04:45,140
All that's left is to put the caps on top.

39
00:04:48,340 --> 00:04:52,860
Our caps are welded too, now we'll clean them up a bit.

40
00:04:53,500 --> 00:04:58,360
This one goes on top, this one on the bottom.

41
00:04:59,960 --> 00:05:01,940
Basically that's it — nothing complicated.

42
00:05:03,740 --> 00:05:06,400
The main thing is the holes line up cleanly.

43
00:05:06,760 --> 00:05:15,540
That's why we tacked them to the radiator first — so once everything's assembled, it all fits together easily, position-wise.

44
00:05:17,020 --> 00:05:17,960
Moving on.

45
00:05:58,360 --> 00:06:04,280
With some simple tools, we pack the boiler.

46
00:06:05,420 --> 00:06:11,080
We've already screwed in a tap for filling water and venting air.

47
00:06:11,940 --> 00:06:19,520
Here we put in an adapter washer for the heating element.

48
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:27,600
And now we'll seal the heating element with this Teflon tape.

49
00:06:28,960 --> 00:06:34,960
It'll go right here in its permanent spot.

50
00:06:39,460 --> 00:06:43,280
Everything's pretty simple — as long as it works.

51
00:06:44,040 --> 00:06:45,520
We're done with assembly.

52
00:06:46,540 --> 00:06:48,050
Here's the finished product.

53
00:06:49,830 --> 00:06:52,110
Wire, everything in place.

54
00:06:53,570 --> 00:07:07,550
Air vent, pressure relief valve, fill tap, expansion tank, and the heating element itself with its wire.

55
00:07:09,030 --> 00:07:23,410
Now we'll measure how many liters of water fit into the system, and how long it takes this 1.5 kW element to heat up the radiator.

56
00:07:24,110 --> 00:07:27,050
And whether it'll heat up at all — whether it gets warm.

57
00:07:27,730 --> 00:07:30,150
First 5 liters going in.

58
00:07:35,350 --> 00:07:36,970
Pour it in faster.

59
00:07:39,330 --> 00:07:41,450
Water flows in nicely.

60
00:07:43,070 --> 00:07:44,910
Come on, faster.

61
00:07:51,130 --> 00:07:53,650
You can hear something bubbling.

62
00:07:57,390 --> 00:07:58,390
Happy about something.

63
00:08:01,650 --> 00:08:05,830
Let's see whether water's coming out here or not.

64
00:08:06,710 --> 00:08:11,830
There — the valve's filled up a bit.

65
00:08:13,610 --> 00:08:18,590
There, the valve's dripping.

66
00:08:20,130 --> 00:08:24,110
OK, faster — pour it in.

67
00:08:27,820 --> 00:08:31,800
Interesting radiator we've got.

68
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:41,100
The system ate the first 5 liters.

69
00:08:42,100 --> 00:08:43,380
Going for the second batch.

70
00:08:51,130 --> 00:08:52,910
The water dives right in.

71
00:08:56,910 --> 00:09:06,870
So, we'll figure out how much fits in this radiator plus the tank we welded.

72
00:09:08,870 --> 00:09:10,410
10 liters in.

73
00:09:10,530 --> 00:09:21,250
Now we start pouring from a 1.5 liter bottle and wait until water starts coming out of the air valve.

74
00:09:23,990 --> 00:09:28,530
There — first drops.

75
00:09:29,610 --> 00:09:31,150
So the system's full.

76
00:09:31,350 --> 00:09:32,510
Pash, pull the funnel out.

77
00:09:33,990 --> 00:09:38,150
We've got a fully-filled water system.

78
00:09:39,190 --> 00:09:43,250
Now we can close our air valve.

79
00:09:45,110 --> 00:09:47,430
No air left in the system.

80
00:09:53,670 --> 00:09:56,030
So how much is left in the bottle?

81
00:09:56,590 --> 00:09:59,490
Close the tap — here's the bottle.

82
00:09:59,610 --> 00:10:03,770
Looks like there's about 10.5 liters of water in the system.

83
00:10:04,390 --> 00:10:11,150
Maybe a touch less than that, but let's call it 10.5 liters of water in the system.

84
00:10:12,930 --> 00:10:15,310
On to field testing.

85
00:10:15,630 --> 00:10:16,990
Thermometer set up.

86
00:10:17,290 --> 00:10:19,350
Outside it's 18 degrees right now.

87
00:10:20,750 --> 00:10:22,970
We'll start the timer here.

88
00:10:23,770 --> 00:10:24,590
And we turn it on.

89
00:10:24,710 --> 00:10:25,230
Off we go.

90
00:10:27,930 --> 00:10:28,810
Got it.

91
00:10:29,010 --> 00:10:36,050
Now let's see how long it takes our system to heat this thing up.

92
00:10:37,830 --> 00:10:43,410
Let's hope the thermometer gives us accurate readings.

93
00:10:44,210 --> 00:10:45,410
And the stopwatch for the time.

94
00:10:46,510 --> 00:10:49,830
This will be over here.

95
00:10:51,610 --> 00:10:52,050
Waiting.

96
00:10:53,530 --> 00:10:57,190
Let's check the time.

97
00:10:58,150 --> 00:11:00,110
Almost 3 minutes.

98
00:11:01,290 --> 00:11:07,230
About a minute and a half ago we started feeling warming here.

99
00:11:10,110 --> 00:11:15,210
Warm water has started moving in these areas.

100
00:11:16,470 --> 00:11:21,150
At this distance you can already feel the warmth from the system.

101
00:11:22,190 --> 00:11:23,770
Almost to the middle.

102
00:11:24,030 --> 00:11:25,390
Now let's watch.

103
00:11:27,030 --> 00:11:29,230
I think the system's going to work.

104
00:11:30,010 --> 00:11:30,750
Warmth's coming.

105
00:11:30,890 --> 00:11:36,810
It's already noticeable here — really nice when the weather outside is like this.

106
00:11:42,490 --> 00:11:43,410
It's heating up.

107
00:11:44,630 --> 00:11:46,250
At the same time we're breaking the system in.

108
00:11:47,010 --> 00:11:50,190
No real cold right now, but with the wind it counts.

109
00:11:51,530 --> 00:11:52,250
We'll see.

110
00:11:52,410 --> 00:11:57,990
If this radiator heats up well, it'll be warm in the room too.

111
00:12:00,890 --> 00:12:07,390
Waiting. At the 8-minute mark we started seeing temperature rise.

112
00:12:08,190 --> 00:12:10,490
Warmth coming from the top.

113
00:12:11,150 --> 00:12:17,190
The radiator's side channels are clearly fully warmed up now.

114
00:12:17,950 --> 00:12:26,350
About 15 cm down from the top, the warm water has clearly started flowing down.

115
00:12:27,090 --> 00:12:32,990
And the reactor itself is already pretty hot.

116
00:12:33,830 --> 00:12:35,470
Checking now.

117
00:12:37,250 --> 00:12:40,350
Almost 10 minutes on the clock.

118
00:12:41,950 --> 00:12:50,230
We can see the system is showing clear signs of life, because it's warm.

119
00:12:51,170 --> 00:12:53,190
You can warm your hands on it now.

120
00:12:54,930 --> 00:12:58,350
The warmth has dropped pretty much down to the middle.

121
00:13:00,270 --> 00:13:02,550
This is great, guys.

122
00:13:03,790 --> 00:13:06,350
So we probably won't need a pump.

123
00:13:09,290 --> 00:13:11,890
14 minutes into the experiment.

124
00:13:12,550 --> 00:13:14,910
Already burning my hand.

125
00:13:15,230 --> 00:13:17,450
The temperature has shot up.

126
00:13:18,670 --> 00:13:21,650
There's noticeable heat convection here.

127
00:13:22,030 --> 00:13:23,610
Warm air is rising.

128
00:13:24,570 --> 00:13:29,470
By feel, the warm water has reached all the way down to the bottom of the radiator.

129
00:13:31,930 --> 00:13:34,910
And it looks like the system's going to work.

130
00:13:35,690 --> 00:13:39,490
Because it's windy outside right now.

131
00:13:40,710 --> 00:13:42,930
The sense of warmth is pretty clear.

132
00:13:45,690 --> 00:13:51,450
Experiment time and temperature.

133
00:13:51,530 --> 00:13:57,830
We're already getting over 30 degrees at the output, given the conditions.

134
00:13:57,990 --> 00:14:00,310
That's how the thermometer's mounted.

135
00:14:00,710 --> 00:14:02,590
But on the hand it's much hotter.

136
00:14:03,510 --> 00:14:04,770
Burning the fingers.

137
00:14:06,510 --> 00:14:15,630
This radiator, of these dimensions, 1.20 m long, is rated for 26 square meters of living space.

138
00:14:22,910 --> 00:14:25,090
You can really see the temperature climbing.

139
00:14:27,390 --> 00:14:32,510
Already too hot to hold here — it burns.

140
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:41,760
OK, 22 minutes into the experiment.

141
00:14:43,660 --> 00:14:45,220
Temperature's rising.

142
00:14:45,440 --> 00:14:47,120
It's really hot here now.

143
00:14:47,200 --> 00:14:49,840
The thermometer's not giving us a good reading.

144
00:14:49,980 --> 00:14:55,120
And you can see that the whole radiator, across its entire length, gives off a uniform flow of heat.

145
00:14:56,020 --> 00:15:01,060
The heat has spread all the way to the far corner.

146
00:15:01,700 --> 00:15:06,440
So even at the farthest point we see the radiator heating up.

147
00:15:06,560 --> 00:15:08,800
Which means it's working over the whole length.

148
00:15:10,120 --> 00:15:11,440
Warm and pleasant.

149
00:15:13,600 --> 00:15:16,660
Time's passing, temperature's rising.

150
00:15:18,120 --> 00:15:20,300
And this you can't hold anymore.

151
00:15:24,020 --> 00:15:33,580
Once the heating element shuts off, we'll measure the surface temperature of the radiator at different points.

152
00:15:33,840 --> 00:15:36,560
We'll put this same thermometer on it and check.

153
00:15:40,920 --> 00:15:42,640
Half an hour of operation.

154
00:15:44,420 --> 00:15:46,980
Better not touch here.

155
00:15:47,380 --> 00:15:48,880
Really burning hot.

156
00:15:49,980 --> 00:15:51,480
Temperature's climbing.

157
00:15:52,480 --> 00:15:58,620
Heat is going all across the whole face of the radiator.

158
00:16:00,260 --> 00:16:04,680
And this part is already heating up noticeably too.

159
00:16:07,300 --> 00:16:11,460
Looks like our experiment is going well.

160
00:16:14,720 --> 00:16:22,240
10.5 liters of water heated up by the system in half an hour — you can't even grab it now.

161
00:16:24,520 --> 00:16:29,900
The thermometer's poorly mounted and isn't reading the full temperature.

162
00:16:30,920 --> 00:16:36,540
Now we'll move on to measuring temperature on the radiator surface.

163
00:16:38,420 --> 00:16:40,800
I'm thinking the farthest corner.

164
00:16:41,540 --> 00:16:44,700
That's the measurement we're most interested in.

165
00:16:45,640 --> 00:16:51,520
We'll just set it there — it'll sit in the airflow.

166
00:16:53,260 --> 00:16:58,300
Wait a bit and find out what's happening here.

167
00:16:59,560 --> 00:17:01,760
There's a decent wind outside.

168
00:17:03,080 --> 00:17:07,080
Temperature's hovering around 18 degrees.

169
00:17:09,420 --> 00:17:15,100
OK, experiment time is 36 minutes.

170
00:17:15,880 --> 00:17:18,360
We just set the thermometer up.

171
00:17:18,840 --> 00:17:24,660
And as you can see, the temperature in the far corner of the radiator is steadily climbing.

172
00:17:25,660 --> 00:17:29,880
The air temperature it's putting out is 50 degrees at this spot.

173
00:17:30,760 --> 00:17:35,520
We understand that in this area it's much hotter than that.

174
00:17:35,640 --> 00:17:36,720
Fingers can't take it.

175
00:17:37,720 --> 00:17:45,660
And the most interesting thing — the top of our system is really hot, but at the bottom you can hold it.

176
00:17:45,780 --> 00:17:56,520
That means one thing — water is moving in the system, circulation is happening, and the radiator really is giving off heat to the air.

177
00:17:57,180 --> 00:18:04,020
If that weren't happening, the whole tank would be heated to the same temperature.

178
00:18:06,360 --> 00:18:07,860
37 minutes.

179
00:18:08,240 --> 00:18:11,240
We'll definitely run this for an hour.

180
00:18:14,060 --> 00:18:17,460
These readings are really, really pleasing us.

181
00:18:17,960 --> 00:18:19,820
Let's try to capture it on camera.

182
00:18:20,480 --> 00:18:24,080
You can see the shimmer of warm air above the radiator.

183
00:18:26,440 --> 00:18:28,380
Looks great.

184
00:18:31,770 --> 00:18:33,430
You can see how it streams up.

185
00:18:35,070 --> 00:18:38,590
If you look at the plants, they kind of blur a bit.

186
00:18:39,710 --> 00:18:44,570
So the heat is going full-on.

187
00:18:45,270 --> 00:18:46,490
The system works.

188
00:18:48,390 --> 00:18:50,170
What's our time?

189
00:18:52,310 --> 00:18:59,050
40 minutes into the experiment, in the far corner.

190
00:19:00,810 --> 00:19:03,910
We're already at 54 degrees.

191
00:19:05,370 --> 00:19:07,890
The system keeps heating up out here.

192
00:19:09,410 --> 00:19:12,370
We're interested in how it heats up.

193
00:19:12,590 --> 00:19:14,850
We'll keep monitoring this spot.

194
00:19:16,010 --> 00:19:18,250
It's significantly hotter here.

195
00:19:21,270 --> 00:19:25,670
I'll say this radiator looks great aesthetically.

196
00:19:26,930 --> 00:19:29,130
Not at all like bi-metal.

197
00:19:29,310 --> 00:19:37,090
No fins where you have to laboriously scrub dust out with a cloth.

198
00:19:37,210 --> 00:19:40,530
Here everything's clean — you can wipe the surface.

199
00:19:41,490 --> 00:19:43,010
Thanks to the manufacturers.

200
00:19:44,490 --> 00:19:46,210
Same surface on the back too.

201
00:19:48,290 --> 00:19:57,630
And the finning inside gives off a really nice flow of warm air.

202
00:19:58,950 --> 00:20:01,890
Let's see who made it.

203
00:20:17,480 --> 00:20:21,260
Nice product.

204
00:20:23,180 --> 00:20:28,940
And it's nice that none of the welds are leaking anywhere.

205
00:20:30,300 --> 00:20:32,900
Our helper here is burning his fingers.

206
00:20:33,220 --> 00:20:37,040
It's really hot — better not to touch.

207
00:20:39,060 --> 00:20:42,100
Moving along in our experiment.

208
00:20:42,260 --> 00:20:47,400
While we were chatting, the temperature climbed even more.

209
00:20:48,860 --> 00:20:52,640
I think we'll catch up to 60, maybe even 70.

210
00:20:53,480 --> 00:20:56,720
45th minute, going on 46.

211
00:20:58,600 --> 00:21:04,220
We've hit the 60-degree mark on our thermometer.

212
00:21:10,660 --> 00:21:13,740
The system's running steady.

213
00:21:14,580 --> 00:21:16,040
Good.

214
00:21:18,420 --> 00:21:27,220
At the 50-minute mark we heard the thermostat trip in the tank.

215
00:21:27,460 --> 00:21:28,020
Click.

216
00:21:28,840 --> 00:21:30,300
Power got cut.

217
00:21:30,420 --> 00:21:36,960
That means the thermostat caught 80 degrees inside the tank.

218
00:21:39,040 --> 00:21:55,700
So here's the thing — when the power shut off, the far end of the radiator was just above 60 degrees while it's 80 degrees here.

219
00:21:55,860 --> 00:21:58,160
That's a 20-degree difference.

220
00:21:58,940 --> 00:22:10,340
A normal state of affairs between the heating element and the spot where maximum heat output happens — the far corner, which is what we care about.

221
00:22:11,320 --> 00:22:19,260
Outside, with wind blowing, this balance will most likely stay.

222
00:22:19,580 --> 00:22:26,560
80 in the heating tank and 60 at the far corner of the radiator.

223
00:22:26,760 --> 00:22:30,480
And that's quite comfortable.

224
00:22:30,820 --> 00:22:32,360
The heat output is really good.

225
00:22:34,740 --> 00:22:38,000
OK, our historic moment.

226
00:22:38,360 --> 00:22:39,740
Coming up on an hour.

227
00:22:39,860 --> 00:22:47,140
We cranked the boiler up to max — 85 degrees — and we heard the click.

228
00:22:51,870 --> 00:22:56,010
Power was cut, and now we're looking at the far corner.

229
00:22:56,010 --> 00:23:01,370
Here we have 64 degrees.

230
00:23:03,350 --> 00:23:06,190
Summing up our experiment.

231
00:23:07,550 --> 00:23:19,650
85 degrees water temperature in the tank, 64–65 degrees of air temperature coming out of the far corner of the radiator.

232
00:23:20,030 --> 00:23:22,250
With windy weather conditions outside.

233
00:23:23,010 --> 00:23:27,190
You can see the temperature conditions.

234
00:23:27,290 --> 00:23:29,790
We've got 18 degrees of warmth outside.

235
00:23:30,150 --> 00:23:33,130
This corresponds to what would happen if the radiator were in a room.

236
00:23:34,530 --> 00:23:37,170
15–18 degrees, not heated.

237
00:23:37,250 --> 00:23:44,110
We turn it on and under the same conditions, the temperature would rise very quickly.

238
00:23:44,250 --> 00:23:50,730
By the way, you can see the temperature is still slowly climbing.

239
00:23:53,250 --> 00:23:57,490
I'd say our experiment is a success.

240
00:23:59,190 --> 00:24:04,130
Then we'll test it in winter conditions and see how it works.

241
00:24:06,510 --> 00:24:09,990
Excellent flow of warm air here.

242
00:24:15,010 --> 00:24:18,530
OK, what did we make it out of?

243
00:24:18,810 --> 00:24:22,730
The pipe was... how big was the pipe, Pash?

244
00:24:23,370 --> 00:24:25,310
114 pipe.

245
00:24:26,630 --> 00:24:29,530
Chinese heating element.

246
00:24:32,110 --> 00:24:35,990
1.5 kW with a temperature regulator.

247
00:24:37,190 --> 00:24:39,210
You can set it however you want.

248
00:24:40,150 --> 00:24:41,570
Plus some fittings.

249
00:24:42,130 --> 00:24:47,230
The whole build cost us 5000 rubles.

250
00:24:47,330 --> 00:24:50,890
The radiator was 600 rubles.

251
00:24:51,590 --> 00:24:56,490
Expansion tank and tap, 180 rubles.

252
00:24:56,990 --> 00:25:02,590
Adapters here, 420 rubles.

253
00:25:04,330 --> 00:25:12,710
Roughly, looking at it all — wiring, everything else, electrodes — about 2000 rubles.

254
00:25:13,150 --> 00:25:16,330
Cost of the boiler itself with its fittings, all of this.

255
00:25:16,470 --> 00:25:19,290
By the way, we also got the valve.

256
00:25:20,390 --> 00:25:27,470
Plus the radiator — call it 7000 rubles for 26 square meters of space.

257
00:25:29,010 --> 00:25:30,470
That's the product.

258
00:25:31,190 --> 00:25:33,370
Temperature measurement.

259
00:25:34,130 --> 00:25:35,470
What's happening here?

260
00:25:37,510 --> 00:25:41,470
You could say, an hour and five minutes of running.

261
00:25:41,850 --> 00:25:43,510
10.5 liters of water.

262
00:25:44,510 --> 00:25:45,970
1.5 kW heating element.

263
00:25:47,230 --> 00:25:48,030
Observing.

264
00:25:50,170 --> 00:25:52,510
Our temperature has gone up.

265
00:25:54,230 --> 00:25:58,030
Well, you could say the sun just peeked out.

266
00:25:58,370 --> 00:25:59,210
We'll account for that too.

267
00:25:59,450 --> 00:26:04,810
But we got 70 degrees of hot air in the far corner, no question.

268
00:26:06,110 --> 00:26:08,210
And the temperature keeps climbing.

269
00:26:13,120 --> 00:26:14,940
Highly recommended to replicate.

270
00:26:15,500 --> 00:26:17,380
And a little closing note.

271
00:26:17,460 --> 00:26:23,300
We were pleasantly surprised when we moved the thermometer to the boiler itself.

272
00:26:25,160 --> 00:26:26,780
Same temperature.

273
00:26:27,340 --> 00:26:32,840
What can we say about this Thermoking radiator?

274
00:26:33,720 --> 00:26:48,900
That regardless of whether it's close to the boiler, in the middle, or in the far corner — the heat output along its entire length is uniform.

275
00:26:49,580 --> 00:26:51,720
The air comes out at the same temperature.

276
00:26:53,380 --> 00:26:55,300
The convector works great.

277
00:26:59,070 --> 00:27:05,250
There's no gradient where one part is hot, another cooler, another cold.

278
00:27:05,330 --> 00:27:11,510
Across the whole face of this radiator the air comes out at the same temperature.

279
00:27:13,190 --> 00:27:13,890
Super!

280
00:27:20,070 --> 00:27:25,350
Time is one hour nine.

281
00:27:27,590 --> 00:27:29,850
We're wrapping up our experiment.

282
00:27:30,910 --> 00:27:32,690
Here's another interesting thing.

283
00:27:33,070 --> 00:27:36,890
It's basically an hour twenty.

284
00:27:36,990 --> 00:27:38,170
We shut it off at the hour mark.

285
00:27:38,830 --> 00:27:47,830
Twenty minutes later, you can see the temperature really isn't dropping much.

286
00:27:47,930 --> 00:27:49,610
The radiator keeps giving off heat.

287
00:27:51,310 --> 00:27:54,210
And we measured it uniformly across the whole surface.

288
00:27:56,310 --> 00:27:58,230
Really cool thing.

289
00:28:00,390 --> 00:28:02,410
Now of course we'll drain the water.

290
00:28:02,570 --> 00:28:10,110
We need to install it, but I'd say it'll keep giving off noticeable heat for another two or three hours.

291
00:28:11,090 --> 00:28:16,710
Say if the power goes out, you won't be left without heat for a while.

292
00:28:16,850 --> 00:28:21,850
10.5 liters of water in the system has some reserve.

293
00:28:23,790 --> 00:28:25,550
And not bad here.

294
00:28:25,970 --> 00:28:27,830
Fingers still burning.
